      {
        "content": "The pervasive use of social media has been linked to increased rates of anxiety, depression, and loneliness, particularly among younger users who are more susceptible to its pressures. The constant exposure to curated, idealized lives can distort reality, leading to low self-esteem and unhealthy comparisons. Moreover, the addictive nature of social media platforms, designed to maximize user engagement, can disrupt sleep patterns and reduce face-to-face interactions, further exacerbating mental health issues. To safeguard user wellbeing, social media must implement reforms prioritizing mental health, such as promoting digital literacy, incorporating mindful usage features, and providing resources for mental health support.",
